711740f-a.text:
23rd Street, north side, east from Tenth Avenue.  On the left, from Tenth to Ninth Avenues, is the original London Terrace, a row of cottages and apartment houses built in 1845 by Bishop Clement C. Moore, author of "The Night before Christmas". These houses were modelled on similar structures popular in London at the time, and for many years constituted a very fashionable address. They were demolished in 1929 and 1930, and replaced by a series of large, modern apartment houses which retain the name London Terrace.

In the right background may be seen the tower of the Metropolitan Life Building.
June, 1925.

711730f-a.text:
(1)
23rd Street, north side, east from 519 West 23rd Street, just west of Tenth Avenue. In the centre, with the cross, is the first Church of the Guardian Angels (Roman Catholic). In the background, some of the apartment houses of the new London Terrace have been completed.
May 31, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The same, a little over a year later. The Church of the Guardian Angels has been torn down for the construction of the elevated structure of the New York Central. The railroad built a new church for the congregation, on Tenth Avenue at the N.W. corner of 21st Street. In the background, the new London Terrace has been completed.
July l6, 1932.
P. L. Sperr.
